The Asian Development Bank warned that tainted food affects 300 million Chinese annually, posing a significant threat.
The report highlighted the potential for a disease outbreak with severe social and economic consequences, surpassing the impact of the SARS epidemic.
Despite efforts to enhance food safety supervision, concerns persist.
Recent incidents, including food poisoning cases and drug safety issues, underscore the urgency for a comprehensive approach.
Calls for a unified supervision mechanism from production to consumption have been made to address the fragmented oversight system.
Strengthening coordination and enforcement measures are crucial to safeguarding public health and building a harmonious society.
